{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"All direct and transitive dependencies are extracted from the manifest and included in the vulnerability check.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Escalation phrase: \"direct and transitive dependencies ... included in the vulnerability check\" implies a handoff boundary between dependency graph extraction and scanner query input. A Unit test on only the extractor could miss a real failure where transitive deps are computed but dropped when building query payloads. Rejected higher levels: behavior text does not require real HTTP/API correctness or OS/subprocess behavior; this can be caught by wiring parser+resolver+query-builder in-process.","test_description":"Run scanner modules together against fixture manifests/lockfiles containing nested transitives; assert the emitted vulnerability-check request set contains all expected direct+transitive packages and versions.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The vulnerability database query returns results that match the exact version ranges in the manifest, not just the package name.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Escalation phrase: \"database query returns results\" + \"exact version ranges\" targets real API query/response semantics. An Integration test with a stub can always honor ranges and miss real failures like incorrect range encoding (e.g., caret/tilde normalization) that causes the external API to return package-name matches for wrong versions. Rejected higher levels: no AI/ML output dependency and no multi-agent sequence.","test_description":"Against a real vulnerability API (or official sandbox endpoint), submit dependencies with closely spaced version ranges and assert returned CVEs correspond only to vulnerable versions within each manifest-specified range.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.72,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The severity sorting places Critical above High above Medium above Low, with CVEs of the same severity sorted by CVSS score.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior is a pure ordering rule: severity precedence and CVSS tiebreak. A single-function comparator/sort test can expose wrong rank mapping or tiebreak direction. No explicit module boundary, OS/network/subprocess, or model-output dependence is required by this behavior.","test_description":"Feed an unsorted CVE list into the sorting function and assert exact ordered output: severity rank first, descending CVSS within equal severity.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.92,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The manifest modification changes only the affected dependency's version, leaving all other entries unchanged.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Core requirement is a localized transformation of manifest content: \"changes only the affected dependency's version\" and \"all other entries unchanged.\" A Unit test on the patching function catches real failures like accidental mutation of sibling dependency entries or unrelated sections. Rejected higher levels: behavior text does not require real filesystem events or external services; in-memory manifest input/output is sufficient.","test_description":"Apply the update function to manifests containing multiple dependencies/sections; assert only the targeted package version changes and byte-for-byte equality for all other parsed entries (or canonicalized structure fields).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The auto-generated pull request is